exual Abuse in the Catholic Church -- tThirteen. Sexual Violence By and Against Trans People -- tFourteen. The Sexual Abuse of Animals -- tList of contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSex crimes, such as rape, child sexual abuse, and intimate partner violence, are increasingly transnational in nature, introducing unique cross-border and cross-cultural challenges for police, the courts, and the law. Policy makers and practitioners are in need of a resource that explores the incidence, prosecution, and treatment of sexual crimes across different countries and cultures.This book is the first to investigate all aspects of sexual crimes and the policy and management initiatives developed to address them from a transnational, global perspective. Introducing an array of tools for reducing the prevalence and consequences of sex crimes, this volume brings together leading scholars in criminology, criminal justice, social work, and law to discuss topics ranging from sex trafficking and sex tourism to pornography, cyberstalking, and sexual abuse in the military and the Catholic church. Case studies track the reporting of these crimes, the methods used to interview victims and perpetrators, and the policies enacted to punish those involved.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aHuman trafficking. 0aSex crimes. 0aTransnational crime. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aAckerman, Alissa R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAckerman, Alissa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAlbanese, Jay S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAugustyn, Rita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurns, Catherine, econtri